You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` using `OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()`, and a **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with the back command and dirty flag

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

    public EditProductViewModel()
    {
        BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnBack);
    }

    async Task OnBack()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/swipe back in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom button handles taps, but the user can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that in `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back-navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page's BindingContext has unsaved changes
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
            is EditProductViewModel vm && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the custom button tap; `OnNavigating` catches swipe/hardware back.
- Set `HasUnsavedChanges = true` whenever a form field changes.
